ngland":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Oversley Green, Warwickshire, England":"Oversley Green, Warwickshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1262–13 August 1295":"1262–13 August 1295","1245–1271":"1245–1271","1262–1295":"1262–1295","1263–1316":"1263–1316","1248–1283":"1248–1283","1272–1342":"1272–1342","1210–1291":"1210–1291","1226–Female":"1226–Deceased","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","5 December 1291":"5 December 1291","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","1283":"1283","1271":"1271","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1226":"1226","1248":"1248","13 August 1295":"13 August 1295","before 4 February 1244":"before 4 February 1244","1245":"1245","11 December 1283":"11 December 1283","1210":"1210","1342":"1342","Tamworth, Staffordshire, England":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Oversley Green, Warwickshire, England":"Oversley Green, Warwickshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marmion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: perhaps an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name. Compare   Merriman  .","English (Lancashire; of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Old French <i>marmion</i> ‘monkey, brat’."],"variants":[{"name":"Merriman","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marmon","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Gloucestershire):","variant of   Marmion  .","variant of <b>Marriman</b>, an occupational name meaning ‘servant of Mary’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":28,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Marmion was born in 1262, in Tamworth, Staffordshire, England, her father, Philip Marm